{"title": "A Critical Look at MCP", "summary": "A Critical Look at MCP\n\nThe text discusses the Model Context Protocol (MCP), an open protocol that aims to standardize how applications provide context to LLMs. The author argues that MCP is poorly engineered, with subpar documentation and implementation guidance. They also criticize the protocol's transport protocol, which is based on Server-Sent Events (SSE) and Streamable HTTP, and argue that it should be replaced with something that mimics stdio. The author also provides an example of implementing an MCP server in Golang, but found the documentation and implementation to be poor. They conclude that the industry should optimize for the most common use-cases and not the corner-cases, and that WebSockets are the appropriate choice for transport over HTTP.", "timestamp": 1746914422.006238, "embedding": [-0.043191052973270416, 0.0126860486343503, 0.04714806750416756, -0.07698196917772293, 0.014390121214091778, -0.023886390030384064, 0.037166301161050797, 0.061917077749967575, 0.022956551983952522, -0.06022419035434723, -0.012225211597979069, 0.026665600016713142, 0.02018173597753048, -0.0028988164849579334, 0.13290046155452728, -0.09531471133232117, 0.15967334806919098, -0.02310236357152462, 0.053543467074632645, -0.012677754275500774, -0.04138077050447464, -0.03027920238673687, -0.04697449877858162, -0.019173117354512215, -0.04645133018493652, 0.065857894718647, 0.0028320979326963425, -0.03948440030217171, 0.025060273706912994, 0.0015301554230973125, 0.009836790151894093, 0.014532088302075863, -0.0140830148011446, 0.006249669473618269, -0.06889380514621735, 0.07217216491699219, 0.027277065441012383, -0.05285446718335152, -0.14268644154071808, 0.02719665691256523, -0.0015690627042204142, -0.05373860150575638, -0.002169207902625203, 0.07984389364719391, -0.05178245157003403, -0.02586713619530201, 0.017377592623233795, 0.031211353838443756, -0.15723615884780884, -0.05732644721865654, -0.06701642274856567, -0.02244313247